  вҲҙ Analyze В«sample-codeвҶ’codeВ» for a new developer joining the project.
    Identify the architectural patterns used (e.g. pub/sub, middleware pipeline,
    saga). Explain how the classes relate to each other and why each abstraction
    exists. Describe the data flow through the system.

-- LLM evaluation:
-- The improved prompt explicitly asks for patterns, relationships, and data flow.
-- The LLM produces a much better summary:

  yield summary вүЎ "This module implements an event-driven architecture with three key patterns: 1) PUB/SUB PATTERN: EventBus provides publish/subscribe via on() (subscribe with priority) and emit() (publish). Handlers are priority-sorted, highest-first. 2) MIDDLEWARE PIPELINE: emit() chains middleware functions that can transform or cancel events before handlers see them вҖ” this is the interceptor/pipeline pattern. 3) SAGA PATTERN: create_saga() orchestrates multi-step operations with automatic compensation (rollback) on failure вҖ” each step pairs with an undo function. TypedBus extends EventBus to add schema validation on emit, ensuring payload structure before dispatch. Data flows: caller вҶ’ emit вҶ’ middleware chain вҶ’ (cancel or continue) вҶ’ priority-sorted handlers вҶ’ results."

-- oracle checks:
--   вҠЁ summary identifies architectural patterns вҶ’ вң“ (names pub/sub, middleware, saga)
--   вҠЁ summary is useful to a new developer вҶ’ partially вң“ (better, but...)

